body:
For the following testcase, LowerState emits an error that it has detected a combinatorial cycle in the design and crashes afterwards:

```mlir
arc.define @i1passthrough(%arg0: i1) -> i1 {
  arc.output %arg0 : i1
}
arc.define @xor(%arg0: i1, %arg1: i1) -> i1 {
  %0 = comb.xor %arg0, %arg1 : i1
  arc.output %0 : i1
}
hw.module @CombinationalLoopDetectedError(%clock: i1, %reset: i1) {
  %1 = arc.state @i1passthrough(%12) clock %clock lat 1 {names = ["flight"]} : (i1) -> i1
  %11 = arc.state @i1passthrough(%13) lat 0 : (i1) -> i1
  %12 = arc.state @xor(%13, %11) lat 0 : (i1, i1) -> i1
  %13 = arc.state @i1passthrough(%reset) lat 0 : (i1) -> i1
}
```

The reason is that in `materializeValue`, all operands are added to the worklist and to the `seen` set then the `%11` operand and its defining operation are popped from the worklist and its operands are processed. At that point inserting the `%13` operand fails because it is already in there. To fix this, each operand could be added to the worklist and processed completely before the next operand is added.
